I"e<p>Just like <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/breathwork-modulates-autonomic-arousal">breathing</a>, <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/optic-flow-modulates-autonomic-arousal">optic flow</a>, or <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/peer-pressure-modulates-autonomic-arousal">peer pressure</a> modulate arousal, so do subliminal cues. Quickly show someone graphic images, too quickly for <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/conscious-awareness-modulates-neural-activity">conscious registration</a>, and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/subcortical-shortcuts-face-a-speed-accuracy-trade-off">subcortical shortcuts will lead to a limbic reaction</a>. Odors, sounds, and others all modulate arousal without <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/conscious-awareness-modulates-neural-activity">conscious awareness</a>.</p>
